        hey what's up mates!  how's everyone's wk going?  well on the billboard hot 100, quite a few country acts dominating the top 10, esp. the top 5.  takes me back to when shania twain's 'you're still the one' would be locked @ #2 spot for about 9 wks. straight.  first time i ever heard of her & she was already this huge country artist.  


        here's my top 10 for now:

        1. buddy holly/that'll be the day

        2.  the mamas & papas/california dreamin'

        3. ed sheeran/shivers

        4. sam hunt/body like a back road

        5. britney/drop dead beautiful

        6. the pointer sisters/jump (for my love)

        7. creed/arms wide open

        8. justin timberlake/nothin' else

        9. johnny hates jazz/shattered dreams

        10.  madonna/future lovers

        also, i highly recommend you all check out buddy holly's & the mamas & papa's music.  buddy holly passed away in 1959 BUT, he was a rock & roll innovator and a huge influence on future artists like the beatles & elton john.  john & paul once went to a buddy holly concert in london or liverpool *can't recall the city* when they both were teenagers.  his song 'that'll be the day' is a perfect example of putting guitar licks in a song that would be standard for the beatles & rolling stones.  

        also the mamas & the papas are an iconic group from the psychadellic era and like a hippie version of abba.  they're the act in my icon pic.  check out 'monday, monday', 'straight shooter' and 'california dreamin'.  



        T

        Chart Review 04/08/2023

        Who needs No.52? The OCC sure don't. Anyways, welcome to the chart where for the first time in a few weeks, ahem...

        NOTHING HAS HAPPENED.

        Except the fact that SOME stuff has happened, but that kinda messes with the script a little. Anyways, Sprinter is at the top for 9 weeks now and I would officially like to stop existing, thank you. Seriously, just go on ACR already and leave us all alone. Unless you're Ed Sheeran, you physically can't just go on a limb and not be challenged at all. Give somebody else a go, for my sanity's sake.

        I could just copy and paste what I said about the Barbie tracks last week, because they ain't going away. O-Rod suffers from not being on the soundtrack and tumbles to 5 (discuss), whilst Billie, Dua, Nicki and Spice all trudge up a spot to leave us all with a mental dilemma. Which one will top the charts in upcoming weeks. Probably Ms. Eilish, 'cause she's streaming champ. I would prefer it if Dua Lipa took top spot instead though.

        Charli XCX, meanwhile, can officially start celebrating with her mates as Speed Drive motors (geddit?) up to 9th position. Great for you, but not for me. I'm probably one of the few people on planet Earth not to have seen the Barbie movie, which, given it's an actually GREAT movie, leaves a bitter taste in my mouth. I also have to edit what I said about I'm Just Ken last week as well, as I should've commented on the fact it sounds like every 80s power ballad ever, rather than, say, every 90s power ballad ever. But that's just me, I'spose.

        In other news, everybody hates Travis Scott, but given he has a No.1 album this week, I assume that means everyone outside his fanbase. Which is huge. UTOPIA slams its way to the summit to give him a first chart-topping collection, and I am somewhat relieved that it didn't go to Anne-Marie in the end. Turns out posing like a pig on your album cover doesn't get you places. Who would've figured. Post Malone is at No.3, and that is that. For the album chart.

        In the singles chart, Travis Scott now has another Top 10 hit, in the form of MELTDOWN, which is generic rap, has Drake on it, so you knew it would be successful, and hasn't tipped into oblivion like the other tracks on the album. Doesn't means it's good (5/10). This is followed by FE!N at 13 (5.1/10), and HYAENA at 21 (7/10), which deserves its high rating because it doesn't really 'sound' like Travis Scott. But then again, this is the guy who made SICKO MODE. So who am I complaining.

        Down at 18, we ask the following question. Can Calvin Harris make a derivative record? The jury is still out on that one, suffice to say that Desire is new in the Top 20 this week, features Sam Smith, who appeared on Promises, so you knew it'd do well, and sounds a bit too much like Miracle for comfort. Heck, even the lyrics seem a little similar. Or maybe that's just my cynisism of dance music seeping through. I really can't tell.

        Stormzy & RAYE fall 11 places, so clearly The Weekend could've done with a bit more work, Kylie is on ACR now, so that , and Chemical seeps its way back into the 40 because, erm, Post Malone wanted it to? Just a thought. Drake & Central Cee clatter their way to 26 with the snappily titled On The Radar Freestyle (5/10), which is so boring I can't be bothered talking about it. This is the 2nd time a CC freestyle has barged its way onto Radio 1's show, following LA Leakers Freestyle back in September. Jealous? I'm not.

        In other news, Sinead's most famous hit sneaks up 15 to reach the 40, although given she's been absent from the Earth committee for a couple weeks now, her chances may be limited. And at 31, a relic of the early-2010s era of dance music strikes back, in the form of Chase & Status, best known for their Top 5 demolishers, Blind Faith, and Lost & Not Found. Their new hit, Baddadan, involves them grabbing Bou, Flowdan, and every dang MC in Britain for what is, in the grand scheme of things, just an average song (5/10).

        Also in the charts this week, Burna Boy and Arrdee have had better days, as Big 7 and One Direction both get caught out by the cynical public, and miss out on the Top 40. Down at 65, a first chart hit for Issey Cross, who popped on Wilkinson's Used To This last year, and will be lucky to come up with ANY original ideas by the end of the year. But to conclude on a high note, I must congratulate Aphex Twin for reaching No.79 with Blackbox Life Recorder 21f. It's his first chart hit for 24 years, and as a fan of SOME of his work, I was really hoping he could deliver on his Top 40 placement in the midweeks. Naturally, this hasn't happened, but I'm glad he's here. Imagine if he was No.1. The whole world would probably cave in.

        And that is that. Ta ta, and close the door on your way out.


        (P.S. During my research, the only Top 40 hit I can think of that isn't listed on this website is Bad by David Guetta. Released in 2014, it peaked at No.23. But it seems the OCC hate that song, so yeah. Oh, and No.52 is Enough Is Enough from Post Malone's new album. There ya go.)
